#: src/interlude_projecting_children.md:1
msgid "Projecting Children"
msgstr ""

#: src/interlude_projecting_children.md:3
msgid ""
"As you build components you may occasionally find yourself wanting to "
"“project” children through multiple layers of components."
msgstr ""

#: src/interlude_projecting_children.md:5
msgid "The Problem"
msgstr ""

#: src/interlude_projecting_children.md:7
msgid "Consider the following:"
msgstr ""

#: src/interlude_projecting_children.md:31
msgid ""
"This is pretty straightforward: if the inner condition is `true`, we want to "
"show `children`. If not, we want to show `fallback`. And if the outer "
"condition is `false`, we just render `()`, i.e., nothing."
msgstr ""

#: src/interlude_projecting_children.md:33
msgid ""
"In other words, we want to pass the children of `<NestedShow/>` _through_ "
"the outer `<Show/>` component to become the children of the inner `<Show/>`. "
"This is what I mean by “projection.”"
msgstr ""

#: src/interlude_projecting_children.md:35
msgid "This won’t compile."
msgstr ""

#: src/interlude_projecting_children.md:41
msgid ""
"Each `<Show/>` needs to be able to construct its `children` multiple times. "
"The first time you construct the outer `<Show/>`’s children, it takes "
"`fallback` and `children` to move them into the invocation of the inner "
"`<Show/>`, but then they're not available for future outer-`<Show/>` "
"children construction."
msgstr ""

#: src/interlude_projecting_children.md:43
msgid "The Details"
msgstr ""

#: src/interlude_projecting_children.md:45
msgid "Feel free to skip ahead to the solution."
msgstr ""

#: src/interlude_projecting_children.md:47
msgid ""
"If you want to really understand the issue here, it may help to look at the "
"expanded `view` macro. Here’s a cleaned-up version:"
msgstr ""

#: src/interlude_projecting_children.md:55
msgid "// children and fallback are moved into a closure here\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/interlude_projecting_children.md:60
msgid "// fallback is consumed here\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/interlude_projecting_children.md:63
msgid "// children is captured here\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/interlude_projecting_children.md:76
msgid ""
"All components own their props; so the `<Show/>` in this case can’t be "
"called because it only has captured references to `fallback` and `children`."
msgstr ""

#: src/interlude_projecting_children.md:78
msgid "Solution"
msgstr ""

#: src/interlude_projecting_children.md:80
msgid ""
"However, both `<Suspense/>` and `<Show/>` take `ChildrenFn`, i.e., their "
"`children` should implement the `Fn` type so they can be called multiple "
"times with only an immutable reference. This means we don’t need to own "
"`children` or `fallback`; we just need to be able to pass `'static` "
"references to them."
msgstr ""

#: src/interlude_projecting_children.md:82
msgid ""
"We can solve this problem by using the [`StoredValue`](https://docs.rs/"
"leptos/latest/leptos/reactive/owner/struct.StoredValue.html) primitive. This "
"essentially stores a value in the reactive system, handing ownership off to "
"the framework in exchange for a reference that is, like signals, `Copy` and "
"`'static`, which we can access or modify through certain methods."
msgstr ""

#: src/interlude_projecting_children.md:84
msgid "In this case, it’s really simple:"
msgstr ""

#: src/interlude_projecting_children.md:101
msgid ""
"// check whether user is verified\n"
"                // by reading from the resource\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/interlude_projecting_children.md:113
msgid ""
"At the top level, we store both `fallback` and `children` in the reactive "
"scope owned by `NestedShow`. Now we can simply move those references down "
"through the other layers into the `<Show/>` component and call them there."
msgstr ""

#: src/interlude_projecting_children.md:115
msgid "A Final Note"
msgstr ""

#: src/interlude_projecting_children.md:117
msgid ""
"Note that this works because `<Show/>` only needs an immutable reference to "
"their children (which `.read_value` can give), not ownership."
msgstr ""

#: src/interlude_projecting_children.md:119
msgid ""
"In other cases, you may need to project owned props through a function that "
"takes `ChildrenFn` and therefore needs to be called more than once. In this "
"case, you may find the `clone:` helper in the`view` macro helpful."
msgstr ""

#: src/interlude_projecting_children.md:121
msgid "Consider this example"
msgstr ""

#: src/interlude_projecting_children.md:126
msgid "\"Alice\""
msgstr ""

#: src/interlude_projecting_children.md:154
msgid "Even with `name=name.clone()`, this gives the error"
msgstr ""

#: src/interlude_projecting_children.md:160
msgid ""
"It’s captured through multiple levels of children that need to run more than "
"once, and there’s no obvious way to clone it _into_ the children."
msgstr ""

#: src/interlude_projecting_children.md:162
msgid ""
"In this case, the `clone:` syntax comes in handy. Calling `clone:name` will "
"clone `name` _before_ moving it into `<Inner/>`’s children, which solves our "
"ownership issue."
msgstr ""

#: src/interlude_projecting_children.md:174
msgid ""
"These issues can be a little tricky to understand or debug, because of the "
"opacity of the `view` macro. But in general, they can always be solved."
msgstr ""
